  \section{8}
    Surface equidstant from $(-1,0,0)$ and plane $x=1$ \\
    That's just a 3-D version of the parabola geometric definition, so it's going to be one of the paraboloids, probably elliptic. \\
    Plane in general form:
    \[
      x-1 = 0
    \]
    Distance from the plane to arbitrary point $(x_0, y_0, z_0)$:
    \[
      D_1 = \frac{\left| x_0 + 0 + 0 -1\right|}{\sqrt{1^2+0^2+0^2}} = \left| x_0 -1\right|
    \]
    Distance from point $(-1,0,0)$ to point $(x_0, y_0, z_0)$:
    \[
      D_2 = \sqrt{(x_0+1)^2 + (y_0)^2 + (z_0)^2}
    \]
    Curve is all points for which $D_1 = D_2$
    \[
      \left| x_0 -1\right| = \sqrt{(x_0+1)^2 + (y_0)^2 + (z_0)^2}
    \]
    \[
      (x_0 -1)^2 = (x_0+1)^2 + (y_0)^2 + (z_0)^2
    \]
    \[
      (x_0)^2 -2x_0 + 1 = (x_0)^2 + 2x_0 + 1 + (y_0)^2 + (z_0)^2
    \]
    \[
      -4x_0 = (y_0)^2 + (z_0)^2
    \]
    \[
     -x_0 = \frac{(y_0)^2}{4} + \frac{(z_0)^2}{4}
    \]
    Which is an elliptic parabaloid opening in the $-x$ direction. (Really $x_0 = x, y_0 = y, z_0 = z$)
